Assistant: It is possible to add the same CSS rules to a single class or style multiple times, but this would only apply to the single rule. If you have multiple rules in your CSS, you could combine them by using a comma between the rules. For example, you could write:

```
<style>
/* CSS rules separated by commas */
#my-div { /* Your CSS rules go here */ }
</style>
```

This would apply the same CSS rules to every instance of the class using the style tag, with the following results:

```
#my-div { color: red; }
```

If you want to apply a single CSS rule multiple times, you can use the `::before` pseudo-class with multiple rules, like so:

```
::before { background: yellow; color: black; }
```

This would apply the rule to the element with the class of `::before`, with the following results:

```
::before { color: yellow; background: black; }

```

